    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are wise to worry about the tone; a poorly phrased reason can feel like a direct attack, which is the last thing you want after a strong final interview.\n\nRegarding the cloud stack, instead of saying they *lack* experience, frame it as a *current, narrow requirement* of this specific role. You can soften the language to sound like a highly specialized need rather than a general weakness.\n\nFor the personal note, a brief, genuine closing line can make a huge difference. It shows you see them as a person, not just a resume.\n\nHere is how you could integrate those changes:\n\n***\n\n**Subject: Update on the Senior Developer Role at [Company Name]**\n\nDear [Candidate Name],\n\nThank you again for investing your time and energy into the final rounds for the Senior Developer position. We were genuinely excited about your candidacy; your grasp of system design was truly impressive, and we felt you connected so well with our team's culture. While we ultimately selected a candidate whose background was a *slightly closer match to the immediate, specialized needs of our current cloud stack*, please know this was an incredibly close decision.\n\nWe were so impressed by your strengths that we would absolutely love to keep your",
